linearmod <- lm(attack ~ max_cp, data = PokemonGOData)

# Create a scatter plot with the regression line
# plot(attack ~ max_cp, data = PokemonGOData, main = "ScatterPlot")
# abline(linearmod, col = "blue")

# Create a scatter plot with the regression line using ggplot2
ggplot(PokemonGOData, aes(x = max_cp, y = attack)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_abline(intercept = linearmod$coefficients[1], slope = linearmod$coefficients[2], col = "blue") +
  labs(title = "ScatterPlot") +
  xlab("max_cp") +
  ylab("attack")

Data Training 70% dan Testing 30%

set.seed(666)
sampellinear <- sample(1:NROW(PokemonGOData), 0.7 * NROW(PokemonGOData))
data_train <- PokemonGOData[sampellinear,]
data_test <- PokemonGOData[-sampellinear,]

ggpairs(data = data_train, columns = c(2, 3, 4, 5))

# Compute and plot wss for k = 2 to k = 15
k.values <- 2:15 

# Define the avg_sil function
avg_sil <- function(k) {
  km.res <- kmeans(Pokemonfix, centers = k, nstart = 25)
  ss <- silhouette(km.res$cluster, dist(Pokemonfix))
  mean(ss[, 3])
}

# extract avg silhouette for 2-15 clusters 
avg_sil_values <- purrr::map_dbl(k.values, avg_sil) 
plot(k.values, avg_sil_values, 
     type = "b", pch = 19, frame = FALSE, 
     xlab = "Number of clusters K", 
     ylab = "Average Silhouettes", ylim=c(0,1))
